(127, '_transient_dash_aa95765b5cc111c56d5993d476b1c2f0', '<div class="rss-widget"><ul><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://wordpress.tv/2013/07/01/joey-kudish-plugin-development-101/'' title='' [&hellip;]''>WordPress.tv: Joey Kudish: Plugin Development 101</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~3/0AQSW293ZYw/disturbing-report-on-wordpress-plugin-security'' title=''Checkmarx, a company founded in 2006 that specializes in automated security code reviews has published a security vulnerability report on the top 50 plugins on the WordPress plugin repository. In the report published on June 18th, 2013 Checkmarx concluded that more than 20% of the 50 most popular WordPress plugins were vulnerable to common web attacks such a [&hellip;]''>WPTavern: Disturbing Report On WordPress Plugin Security</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://wordpress.tv/2013/07/01/reid-peifer-where-the-heck-is-everyone-working-with-distributed-teams/'' title='' [&hellip;]''>WordPress.tv: Reid Peifer: Where The Heck Is Everyone? Working with Distributed Teams</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://nacin.com/2013/07/01/firefox-makes-a-decision-removes-an-option/'' title=''Back in 2011, I wrote about how we need to make decisions in open source. This is not a new idea — it is rooted in the guiding philosophies for WordPress to make decisions, not options. Perhaps unsurprisingly, Hacker News is now up in arms about Firefox 23 removing the “Disable Javascript” option. I’m really glad to see ex-Mozilla guy Gregory Koberger with t [&hellip;]''>Andrew Nacin: Firefox makes a decision, removes an option</a></li><li><a class=''rsswidget'' href=''http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~3/BjB9fyGUmK8/the-daily-plugin-for-7-1-2013'' title=''Hope you had an enjoyable weekend. It’s time to start your week with another fresh batch of plugins from the WordPress Plugins Repository. As we venture into the details of each plugin, bear i